initial_story: My observation is there exists unequal share of State monies with its residents, before all the Urban residents get defensive please hear me out. Presently no one except Corporations pay State income taxes. No individual pays state taxes. I noticed state funded bicycle paths, road maintenance, defunct Docks, powerful politicians pet projects such as office buildings, state troopers etc, etc. all these fundings and more are not necessary within City limits, I was amazed at how much our state provides city functions in the bigger cities thus growing the state budget, I saw on tv last night how adg&g was showing the little ones how to ice fish, couldn't the parents do that? yes I pay property taxes. But I will guarantee you once our City folk get the full bill with out the State monies we will not be as wasteful, on the office building...rent what space you need and help the office rental marked. In my business I just retired from,I would ask my managers, "how do you stop spending money"?
stories: I'm not saying it's all bad, but when I look at my property tax bill, I see that a significant chunk goes towards funding these very same projects and programs that benefit the urban residents. Meanwhile, in our rural areas, we're struggling to get basic services like reliable internet and cell phone reception. It's like we're being taken advantage of. And don't even get me started on the so-called "economic development" initiatives that only seem to benefit the already wealthy. I'm not anti-urban, but I do think it's time we re-evaluate how our state's resources are being allocated. Maybe we should have a more transparent and fair system, where everyone contributes and everyone benefits.

I think it's time we start asking some tough questions and demanding change. We need to make sure our rural communities are getting the support they need to thrive, not just survive. And it's not just about infrastructure, it's about creating opportunities for our kids and grandkids to stay in our communities and build their own futures. I'm not asking for handouts, I'm asking for fairness and equity. We deserve better than to be treated like afterthoughts in our own state.
